      "titleTr": "# Editorial: Record-Breaking Tourist Arrivals in Korea — Spreading Benefits to Local Regions Is the Key Challenge\n\nKorea welcomed a record 14.2 million foreign visitors last year, marking the first time the nation has surpassed the 14 million threshold. This achievement is cause for celebration, as it demonstrates Korea's growing appeal as a global tourist destination and validates the government's tourism promotion efforts.\n\nHowever, beneath this positive headline lies a critical reality that demands attention: the overwhelming concentration of tourism in Seoul and a handful of major cities. The capital and its surrounding regions attract the vast majority of foreign visitors, while provincial areas struggle to capture their share of the tourism boom. This imbalance threatens to undermine the potential benefits of record-breaking arrivals.\n\nFor tourism to truly contribute to balanced regional development and economic growth nationwide, the distribution of visitors must be more equitable. Local regions possess distinct cultural heritage, natural attractions, and culinary offerings that rival those of major cities. Yet they remain largely overlooked by international tourists due to inadequate infrastructure, limited promotion, and poor accessibility.\n\nThe government and tourism industry must now focus on dispersing visitor flows beyond Seoul. This requires targeted marketing campaigns highlighting regional attractions, improvements to transportation networks connecting provinces to major hubs, and support for local businesses to enhance service quality. Regional tourism development is not merely an economic issue—it is essential for sustainable growth and equitable prosperity across the nation.\n\nThe record number of visitors represents an opportunity. Whether Korea can transform this opportunity into genuine nationwide benefits will depend on how effectively tourism is distributed to local regions.",
