      "bodyTr": "# Foreign Visitor Numbers to Korea Hit Record High in First Quarter\n\nForeign visitors to Korea in the first quarter of this year reached 4.76 million, marking an all-time high for the period and representing a 23 percent increase from the same quarter last year. The Ministry of Culture, Sports and Tourism attributed this surge to \"the global popularity of Korean culture.\" Last month's BTS concert at Gwanghwamun Plaza is believed to have played a significant role in driving the figures.\n\nThe phenomenon of Korean culture serving as a catalyst for tourism has become increasingly evident in recent years. A 2024 survey by the Korean Culture and Tourism Research Institute found that foreign visitors cited \"Korean Wave content\" and \"traditional Korean culture\" as the top two reasons for their interest in visiting Korea.\n\nWhat is particularly encouraging is that this interest has expanded beyond Seoul to regional areas rich in traditional culture. According to ministry data, foreign arrivals through provincial airports surged 50 percent year-over-year in the first quarter. A significant portion of visitors using regional airports subsequently venture into local tourism. The proportion of foreign visitors to Korea who visited regional areas in the first quarter reached 34.5 percent, a 3 percentage point increase from the previous year, while their length of stay in regions and card spending within those areas jumped 36 percent and 27 percent respectively.\n\nWhile it may be premature to characterize foreign tourism to Korea as undergoing a structural shift, the fact that international visitors are increasingly venturing into provinces, staying longer, and spending more is undeniably positive.\n\nPresident Lee Jae-myung's mention on the 14th at a state council meeting of coordinating local residents, small business owners, and tourism activists—with administrative support—reflects an intention to nurture this trend. Consequently, the Ministry of the Interior and Safety has proposed establishing public-private tourism councils at the city, county, and district levels, while the Culture Ministry has expressed its commitment to supporting regional tourism activists.\n\nThe direction of public-private cooperation to actively leverage private sector ideas is sound. However, for results to materialize, local administrative efficiency must be bolstered in areas such as transportation, infrastructure, and regulations, while political considerations that hinder effective decision-making must be excluded.\n\nTourism now represents one of Korea's most pressing solutions to regional hollowing—a critical",
